{"title_page": "Sanguis Venenatus", "text_new": "{{coi|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Elegy for strings by Andrew March in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to tainted blood.}}\n{{italic title}}\n\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Sanguis Venenatus''\n| translation         = Tainted blood\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Andrew March]]\n| catalogue           = \n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[String orchestra#repertoire|Music for strings]]\n| composed            = {{start date|2009}}\n| premiere_date       = {{Start date|2010|03|20|df=y}} \n| premiere_location   = [[Todmorden]], [[West Yorkshire]]\n| premiere_conductor  = Nicholas Concannon Hodges\n| Premiere_performers = Todmorden Orchestra\n| publisher           = \n| published           = \n| first_recording     = {{Start date|2011|07|09|df=y}} Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| form                =  [[Ternary form]]\n| duration            = {{Duration|m=5|s=30}}\n| scoring             = [[String orchestra]]\n| misc                = Written in memory of haemophiliacs who lost their lives due to contaminated blood\n}}\n\n'''''Sanguis Venenatus''''' is an elegy for strings by English composer [[Andrew March]] written in memory of [[haemophiliac]]s (and others) affected by the [[United Kingdom tainted blood scandal|Tainted Blood Scandal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday \u2013 Verity Sharp, Late Junction \u2013 BBC Radio 3|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06g6456|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sanguis Venenatus \u2013 Andrew March & Moravian Philharmonic Strings Song \u2013 BBC Music|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802015204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/tracks/n3x4nm|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Composers \u2013 Alliance Publications, Inc.|url=http://www.apimusic.org/march-andrew-b.1973.html|website=www.apimusic.org|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Gramophone1\">{{cite news |last=Rosenberg |first=Donald |date=March 2013 |title=Eight works for string orchestra from four different orchestras. |url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/34724/page/9|work=Gramophone |location=UK |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Todmorden1\">{{cite web|title=Reviews \u2013 Todmorden Orchestra|url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/|website=Todmorden Orchestra}}</ref><ref>{{cite archive |first= |last= |item = Sanguis Venenatus |item-url =https://rcm.koha-ptfs.co.uk/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=249942 |type = Audio CD |item-id = |date = 2012 |page= |pages= |fonds = |series = NV5895 Navona Records |collection = In Dimensions : works for string orchestra|repository = RCM Library Catalogue|institution = Royal College of Music |location = London |oclc= |accession= |ref=CD11802}}</ref> The elegy was included in a service on 30 March, 2011 at [[Westminster Abbey]]<ref name=\"Westminster1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.westminster-abbey.org/media/4247/chronically-sick-disabled-persons-act-service.pdf |title=A service to mark the 40th anniversay of the coming into effect of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 March 2011 |website= |publisher=Westminster Abbey |access-date=2020-04-18 |quote=}}</ref> to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the UK legislation&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970). ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was dedicated to the late [[Alf Morris|Lord Morris of Manchester]], to recognise his long\u2013standing support and advocacy for persons with haemophilia.<ref name=\"Navona1\">{{cite web|title=Dimensions&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;Works for String Orchestra|url=https://www.eclassical.com/shop/17115/art66/4717266-4e7070-0896931000956.pdf|website=EClassical.com|publisher=Navona Records}}</ref> \n\n==Composition==\nIn 2009, Andrew March completed a cycle of 10 string quartets based on the characteristics of [[Diurnality|diurnal]] [[birds of prey]]. The fifth piece, entitled ''Elegy for an Unsuspecting [[Red phalarope|Phalarope]]'' was inspired by the image of a huge [[Common buzzard|buzzard]] snatching a small grey [[Wader|wading bird]].<ref name=\"Navona1\" /> The photograph, which appeared in [[The Times]] on 16th January 2009, was taken by two birdwatchers, Paul Freestone and Tim Twiggs at [[St Gothian Sands]] in [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite news |last=de Bruxelles|first=Simon |date=16 January 2009 |title=Horrified twitchers watch as starving buzzard kills rare phalarope |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/horrified-twitchers-watch-as-starving-buzzard-kills-rare-phalarope-53hkjvdddgc |work=The Times |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=|first= |date=16 January 2009 |title=Buzzard kills rare visitor to British shores |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/gallery/2009/jan/16/wildlife-cornwall |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> For March, this image became a poignant metaphor for the disaster which befell thousands of haemophiliacs who were treated with [[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom|contaminated blood products]].<ref name=\"Todmorden1\" /> The quartet was subsequently reworked for the forces of a full string orchestra, after which the elegy was given the Latin title, ''Sanguis Venenatus''; the closest possible rendering of \u2033Tainted Blood\u2033.<ref name=\"Navona1\" /> \n\nThe score bears the inscription: ''\u2033This work is dedicated to all the haemophiliacs and others who have lost their lives through contaminated blood and blood products.\u2033''  In the April 2013 edition of the European Haemophilia Consortium newsletter, the composer talked in personal terms about what motivated him to write the elegy:\n{{quote |''It is difficult to express in words exactly how I felt at losing so many of my friends, other than to say I was wracked with grief. As a composer, this build\u2013up of emotion had to go somewhere and it is my wish that in writing the elegy, I have managed to capture some of this strength of feeling.''<ref>{{cite report |editor-first1=Amanda|editor-last1=Bok|date=April 2013 |title=EHC Newsletter |url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/28554873/april-2013-ehc |publisher=European Haemophilia Consortium (EHC) |location=Brussels|page=27|access-date=2020-04-20|quote=Andrew March: ''Elegy dedicated to victims of contaminated blood''}}</ref>}}\n\n==Recording==\nThe piece was recorded in Reduta Hall, [[Olomouc]], [[Czech Republic]] on 9th July, 2011, by 50 string players from the [[Moravian Philharmonic]] under conductor, [[Petr Vronsk\u00fd]]. ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was released as the fourth track on the CD album ''Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra'' by Navona Records (NV5895) on 13 November 2012.<ref>{{cite book | title=Dimensions \u2013 Works for String Orchestra| oclc=1114084658}}</ref> The ''Dimensions'' album was reviewed in Gramophone in March 2013, where [[Donald Rosenberg]] said that ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was \u2033intensly felt\u2033 and that the elegy was characterised by \u2033slow, aching lines and mild dissonances\".<ref name=\"Gramophone1\" />\n\n==Performances==\nThe world premi\u00e8re of ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was given on Saturday 20th March, 2010, at [[Todmorden]] Town Hall, by the strings of the Todmorden Orchestra under conductor Nicholas Concannon Hodges. The premi\u00e8re was followed by positive review describing the one\u2013movement elegy as a first\u2013hand musical metaphor for thousands of haemophiliacs given contaminated blood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk/reviews/ |title=Reviews: March 20th 2010, Todmorden Town Hall |last=Issac |first=Stuart |date=20 March 2010 |website=www.todmordenorchestra.org.uk |publisher=Todmorden Orchestra |access-date=2020-04-22 |quote=}}</ref> On Wednesday 30th March, 2011, the elegy received a second performance during a commemorative service at Westminster Abbey with the strings of the London Charity Orchestra under William Carslake. The service celebrated the 40th anniversary of the enactment of the Chronically Sick and Disabled Persons Act (1970).<ref name=\"Westminster1\" /><ref name=\"Navona1\" />\n\n==Broadcasts==\nThe first known radio broadcast of ''Sanguis Venenatus'' was on [[WPRB|WPRB 103.3]] fm [[Princeton, New Jersey]], on 28th November 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://andrewmarch.com/59274/97146.html |title= News updates for Sanguis Venenatus|date=2012-08-28 |access-date=2020-04-24 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180823023841/http://andrewmarch.com/59274/97146.html |archive-date=2012-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.classicaldiscoveries.org/playlist20121128c_g.html|title= Classical Discoveries|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=28 November 2012 |website= WPRB 103.3 FM|publisher= |access-date=2020-04-24 |quote= ''Sanguis Venenatus'' (Tainted Blood)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contaminated blood scandal in the United Kingdom]]\n*''[[Marine \u2013 \u00e0 travers les arbres]]'' (winning piece of the first Masterprize)\n*[[R (March) v Secretary of State for Health]] (judicial review involving victims of contaminated blood products)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W4gy-7IlUqg YouTube, (''Sanguis Venenatus'')]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1hJ4O21moxc YouTube (Deezer), (''Sanguis Venenatus'' Moravian Philharmonic Orchestra)]\n* [http://radiofy.se/artists/828892-andrew-march/songs/1-sanguis-venenatus Radiofy, ''Sanguis Venenatus'' av Andrew March] {{In lang|sv}}\n* [http://www.pandora.com/artist/moravian-philharmonic-orchestra/dimensions-works-for-string-orchestra/sanguis-venenatus-for-orchestra/TRdV7X5gcgx2bxJ Pandora (Streaming) ''Sanguis Venenatus'' (Dimensions)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Works about contaminated haemophilia blood products]]\n